00:02:19.120 --> 00:02:23.310
He also wrote a biography
of Charles Lindbergh

00:02:23.310 --> 00:02:26.370
and it also won the Pulitzer Prize.

00:02:26.370 --> 00:02:30.850 position:56%
And of course, he has written a
biography of Woodrow Wilson as well.

00:02:30.850 --> 00:02:36.100
And that very much ties into
what we're talking about today,

00:02:36.100 --> 00:02:39.310
World War I on the
hundredth anniversary of it.

00:02:39.310 --> 00:02:43.280
And I want to say a bit about
the craft of being a biographer.

00:02:43.280 --> 00:02:44.760
Think about what it takes.

00:02:44.760 --> 00:02:46.650
You have to be a researcher.

00:02:46.650 --> 00:02:48.300
You have to be an editor.

00:02:48.300 --> 00:02:50.130
You have to be an author.

00:02:50.130 --> 00:02:54.670
You must have a point of view
but you must not be a partisan.

00:02:54.670 --> 00:02:59.910
You must provide a vista for the
reader to have a view of history

00:02:59.910 --> 00:03:03.900
without narrowing the range
of the reader's vision.

00:03:03.900 --> 00:03:09.870 position:56%
That's a rare gift, and there are at
any time in any great nation only 10

00:03:09.870 --> 00:03:12.640
or 20 people really, I think,
operating at the height

00:03:12.640 --> 00:03:16.020
of the craft, and we are about
to hear from one such person.

00:03:16.020 --> 00:03:19.510
So please join me in
welcoming Scott Berg.

00:03:19.510 --> 00:03:27.880
[ Applause ]

00:03:27.880 --> 00:03:29.180
&gt;&gt; A. Scott Berg: Thank
you very much.

00:03:29.180 --> 00:03:32.090
That was a wonderful introduction.

00:03:32.090 --> 00:03:33.460
I'm most appreciative.

00:03:33.460 --> 00:03:37.360 position:56%
And I want to thank the National
Endowment of the Humanities as well,

00:03:37.360 --> 00:03:40.250
which has been a great supporter
of the Library of America

00:03:40.250 --> 00:03:42.760
which published this book and
has been a great supporter

00:03:42.760 --> 00:03:45.340
of this book in particular.

00:03:46.670 --> 00:03:50.750
This book represents something
quite special, certainly to me,

00:03:50.750 --> 00:03:53.240 position:56%
and I hope to all of you ultimately.

00:03:53.240 --> 00:03:56.110
Because we are celebrating,
in a way,

00:03:56.110 --> 00:03:59.150
two anniversaries with this book.

00:03:59.150 --> 00:04:02.400
The first is, this is
the 35th anniversary

00:04:02.400 --> 00:04:04.520
of the Library of America.

00:04:04.520 --> 00:04:07.070
I don't know if you know
about the Library of America.

00:04:07.070 --> 00:04:11.530
If you don't, I don't know what
